fields.label_text:
CROZIER
Bronze, cast, chased and gilt
South Netherlandish; about 1530
From the Abbey of St. Hubert near Liege 
Formerly in the collections of Montfort, Soltikoff and Magniac
A crozier is the staff of office of a bishop, abbot or archbishop, and represents his authority over, and responsibility for, his flock, its shape inspired by that of a shepherd's crook. The patron saint of the Abbey from which this crozier comes, Hubert, is shown here standing in the crook. At his feet is a stag crouching, with a crucifix between its antlers. This alludes to a legendary episode in the saint's life, that when hunting in the forest on Good Friday he met a stage with a crucifix between its antlers, and was converted to leading a more godly life. The Abbey owned relics of St. Hubert, and was an important pilgrimage centre. Around the knop of the crozier are cast figures and saints, one of whom is St. Beregisus, founder of the Abbey.

fields.descriptive_line: Cast, chased and gilt bronze. South Netherlands, around 1530, from the Abbey of St Hubert near Liege.; Church plate, Continental
